\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Distribution of OLS estimator and IV estimator using $Gx$ across 100 simulations. The OLS estimator is biased due to endogeneity, while the IV estimator using $Gx$ is also biased but less so. By applying Proposition 5 with $G^2 x$ as the second instrument, we can compute bounds on $\beta $ that account for the imperfect nature of $Gx$, represented by black horizontal lines. }}{7}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:ols_iv_bounds}{{4}{7}{Distribution of OLS estimator and IV estimator using $Gx$ across 100 simulations. The OLS estimator is biased due to endogeneity, while the IV estimator using $Gx$ is also biased but less so. By applying Proposition 5 with $G^2 x$ as the second instrument, we can compute bounds on $\beta $ that account for the imperfect nature of $Gx$, represented by black horizontal lines}{figure.4}{}}
